important_phrase: Despite continuing reports that sales   levels are below what they consider to be normal, contacts anticipate little to   moderate upward price pressure from improving sales levels over the next 12   months
Firms continued to   note difficulty filling specialized positions
Credit availability increased and competition among lenders for   loans remained strong
The District's   manufacturing sector continued to expand modestly in April and May
In the   short-term, homebuilders expect sales and construction to be flat to slightly up   compared with a year earlier
Reports from District   retailers indicated that consumer spending improved in April and May
Except for software and IT services where growth continues to be   relatively strong, few firms are doing substantial hiring

The number of permanent and   temporary-to-permanent placements continues to grow, albeit modestly; however,   two contacts say this trend is likely attributable to their own internal efforts   to boost permanent hires, rather than improvements in labor-market fundamentals
New England   software and information technology firms report mixed results through May, with   some experiencing continued growth and others citing modest slowdowns
The outlook among contacts is that, barring significant macroeconomic   turmoil, conditions should remain flat or improve slightly in the rest of the   year
Consumer spending is   particularly strong on adult clothing, household goods, and items related to   home improvement and maintenance
Milk prices decreased, and   prices are low enough to trigger some concerns about margins for dairy   operations
Commodity prices moved   lower, and wage increases remained moderate
Stel prices softened, with one contact noting that weaker demand in Europe   and Asia had contributed to the decline
Business loan demand remained limited apart from steady growth in   refinancing and capital replacement
Demand for heavy   equipment, though still strong, decreased slightly
Vaancy rates edged lower, but remained elevated, particularly for retail   properties
Consumer spending increased at a slower   rate in April and May
Conventional drilling   has slowed due to very low natural gas prices
Exploration   and production in shale gas expanded, even as the demand for coal has slowed
Consumer credit pricing held steady
Input costs were stable, with any   upward pressure being characterized as modest
Our contacts expect that business will continue to   slowly improve as the year progresses
Purchases of   used vehicles were fairly steady year-over-year--inventories are building and   prices declined slightly
Respondents at energy-related firms said drilling   activity remained strong, and the District rig count grew modestly over the past   six weeks
Drought   conditions improved
Retailers said selling   prices were stable, although food prices increased
Refiners said margins improved slightly in early May
Rental rate increases slowed, but remain relatively healthy
Retail sales grew modestly over the   comparable period from a year ago and performed in line with contacts'   expectations
Agricultural conditions improved since the   last survey
The Tenth District economy improved moderately in late April and May
Wge   pressures increased since the previous survey but remained fairly low
In the recent survey period, bankers generally   reported slightly stronger loan demand, improving loan quality, and increased   deposits
Both durable and non-durable   goods manufacturers reported increased production
Residential real estate   activity improved during the most recent survey period, and commercial activity   was solid
Consumer spending increased in the   retail, restaurant and tourism sectors but declined in the auto sector
Activity in the energy and mining   sectors grew
Price increases were generally subdued
Manufacturers in several   areas reported difficulty recruiting skilled workers, particularly welders
) found that production expanded in Minnesota and the   Dakotas
Commercial real estate market activity increased
Consumer spending increased   modestly
Agricultural conditions   generally improved since the previous report
Consumer spending was   unchanged or up modestly
Overall upward wage   pressures continued to be fairly modest
Reports on mortgage lending generally indicated slow improvement
Demand for nonfinancial services   was generally stable to slightly stronger since the previous report
Boston's relatively   strong commercial market continued to generate robust investor interest,   although commercial property sales in the New York District remained slow
Retail spending was flat to   modestly positive in nearly all Districts
Rental   markets remain strong, with rents rising due to tight inventory levels
Respondents also indicate some decline in   average deposit rates
In addition, business contacts in manufacturing   and other sectors note a slower pace of input price increases and steady to   somewhat higher selling prices
Commercial property sales activity remains slow
Wolesale   and retail credit conditions remain favorable and continue to improve
Retailers continue to expect steady improvement
Manufacturing firms report lower cost factors since the last Beige Book
Most contacts report solid credit quality
New to the list of concerns and   uncertainties about the outlook is the increasing worry that political gridlock   will lead to large cuts in defense-related production through sequestration
Residential builders report   some softening in May traffic and sales due to a combination of typical seasonal   slowing and a drop-off from the atypically strong first-quarter sales
Retail   contacts remain cautiously optimistic
In South Carolina, cotton planting   was slightly ahead of schedule, and planting of peanuts was well ahead of its   normal pace
Price increases--both paid   and received--generally slowed
According to our latest survey, District wage gains in manufacturing were   slightly lower than a month ago, while the pace of wages in the service sector   increased
Lending activity increased modestly across most   segments of the market
According to our latest survey, both raw materials prices and finished goods   prices grew at a somewhat slower pace than a month ago
Commercial real estate leasing and construction was flat or moderately   improving in recent months, although pockets of weakness persisted
Shopper   traffic was unchanged since our last report and big-ticket sales declined,   according to a recent survey
Orders and sales expanded further for most   crop and livestock products, spurred in part by strong growth in overseas   exports
Price increases for final   goods and services were very modest, and upward wage pressures were quite   limited overall
Price inflation remained quite limited   for most final goods and services
Demand for consumer credit appeared largely unchanged
Demand   improved slightly for steel manufacturers but remained depressed for   manufacturers of wood products
However, contacts   noted widening signs of improved demand
Retail sales grew modestly on   balance
More than 88   percent of the winter wheat crop was rated as fair or better, while 77 percent   or more of pasture land was also similarly rated in all District states
Residential real estate market conditions have improved   moderately
Meanwhile, credit standards for   consumer loans ranged from basically unchanged to somewhat eased, while demand   ranged from moderately weaker to moderately stronger
In contrast, firms in software development   services announced plans to hire additional workers and expand operations
Commercial and industrial construction   activity improved moderately throughout most of the District
Twenty percent of the retailers noted that their inventories   were too high, while 12 percent indicated that their inventories were too low
